Henry II, the first Plantagenet king, came to the throne in 1154 after a turbulent civil war. His marriage to **Eleanor of Aquitaine**  one of the most extraordinary women of the Middle Ages  was both romantic and political. Eleanor had once been queen of France, and by marrying Henry she brought the vast Duchy of Aquitaine under English control.

Together they had a brood of strong-willed children, many of whom turned against their father. Their sons included Richard (later the Lionheart) and John, whose rivalry would shape the monarchy. Henry II built a legal and administrative framework that gave England a stronger monarchy, but his reign was also marred by strife, including his deadly quarrel with Thomas Becket, Archbishop of Canterbury.

---

## **King John (11991216) and Isabella of Angoulme**

Henrys youngest son, **John**, inherited the throne after Richard the Lionhearts death. Johns reign was infamous  he lost Normandy and much of the Angevin Empire in France, earning him the nickname Lackland.

Johns marriage to **Isabella of Angoulme** brought temporary alliances, but his heavy-handed rule and constant taxation sparked baronial revolts. In 1215, the rebel barons forced him to seal the **Magna Carta**, a document that placed the first legal limits on royal authority. Though John tried to renege on it, the Magna Carta endured as a cornerstone of constitutional government.

Johns son, Henry, would inherit both the throne and the unrest.

## **Henry III (12161272) and Eleanor of Provence**

Johns young son, **Henry III**, became king at only nine years old. His mother and trusted nobles ruled in his name until he came of age. Henrys long reign was marked by piety and devotion to art and architecture  most famously, his rebuilding of **Westminster Abbey** in Gothic splendor.

He married **Eleanor of Provence**, whose foreign relatives gained influence at court, angering the English barons. The kingdom slipped into civil war when Simon de Montfort led a rebellion. Though Henry eventually prevailed, the conflict set lasting precedents for the role of Parliament.

## **Edward I (12721307): The Warrior King**

Henry IIIs son, **Edward I**, was one of the great warrior kings of medieval England. Tall and imposing, he earned the nickname Longshanks. His marriage to **Eleanor of Castile** was a rare love match; their deep bond is remembered in the series of Eleanor Crosses Edward raised after her death in 1290. He later remarried **Margaret of France**, securing peace with the French crown.

Edward I subdued Wales, building mighty castles that still dominate its landscape, and fought bitter wars in Scotland against leaders like William Wallace and Robert the Bruce. His reign strengthened royal justice and administration, but constant warfare drained the treasury.
